_b-1024x514.jpg\";s:5:\"width\";i:1024;s:6:\"height\";i:514;s:9:\"mime-type\";s:10:\"image/jpeg\";}s:18:\"catchbase-featured\";a:4:{s:4:\"file\";s:35:\"5036054553_f798975c5a_b-780x439.jpg\";s:5:\"width\";i:780;s:6:\"height\";i:439;s:9:\"mime-type\";s:10:\"image/jpeg\";}}s:10:\"image_meta\";a:11:{s:8:\"aperture\";i:0;s:6:\"credit\";s:14:\"Jonathan Banks\";s:6:\"camera\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"caption\";s:998:\"The Liberia Media Projects third and largest annual peace festival brought together participants from across the ethnic divide to promote reconciliation in West Africa through traditional and modern arts and communication. Artists from neighbouring Guinea, Sierra Leone and Côte dIvoire joined local participants in theatre, dance and dialogue over the course of three days in Ganta, Nimba County.\nThe festival is a celebration of peace after years of war in Liberia, and an invitation for reconciliation in the wider subregion. Fourteen years of civil war destroyed much of the social cohesion and infrastructure that is now needed to support peaceful co-habitation between different groups in rural Liberia. The peace festival offers a space to voice grievances and explore constructive means of reconciliation.\nAs Liberians still share a rich cultural heritage replete with songs, poetry, music, dance, costume and theatre, the arts offer unique opportunities for promoting unity and peace.\";s:17:\"created_timestamp\";i:0;s:9:\"copyright\";s:58:\"Jonathan Banks www.photo-banks.com for International Alert\";s:12:\"focal_length\";i:0;s:3:\"iso\";i:0;s:13:\"shutter_speed\";i:0;s:5:\"title\";s:64:\"Dancing at The Liberia Media Project in Liberia, 8 - 10 March 20\";s:11:\"orientation\";i:0;}}'),(269,80,'_wp_attachment_is_custom_background','catch-base'),(270,125,'_edit_lock','1432218888:1'),(271,132,'_edit_lock','1432219450:1'),(272,132,'_edit_last','1'),(273,95,'_edit_lock','1431682272:1'),(274,141,'_wp_attached_file','2015/05/CSBP_Sec1_0.pdf'),(275,142,'_wp_attached_file','2015/